	<td valign="Top">
<p align="center"><font size="4"><b>MESSAGE FROM THE CHAIRMAN</b></font><font size="2"> </font><br>
</p>
<p><font size="4"><b>To Kmart Shareholders:</b></font> <br>
<p>
Kmart's financial results in 1995 were disappointing. However,
this performance represents an extraordinary amount of work completed
in order to lay the foundation for a bottoming out of Kmart's financial
decline and a return to profitability this year. </p>
<p>Since joining Kmart in June of 1995, my top priority has been
to build a management team with a &quot;can-do&quot; attitude that permeates
all of our interaction with customers, vendors, shareholders, and
one another. Changing the way we act and interact will continue
to be one of my top priorities in 1996. That is why our entire
management team recently signed our Pledge to Excellence and
committed themselves to making Kmart a leader in the retail
arena once again. While a pledge may not seem particularly important
in the broad scheme of Kmart's turnaround, I am very excited by
the energy, enthusiasm, and commitment of our associates to
improve Kmart. </p>
<p>We have plenty of work to do. In fiscal 1995, the Company
reported a net loss from continuing operations of $100 million, or
$0.23 per share. Including a non-cash charge of $390 million, or
$0.85 per share, for the adoption of Financial Accounting
Standard No. 121 (FAS 121), the net loss for the year was $571
million, or $1.25 per share. </p>
<p>Clearly, there is still a long way to go, but if you talk to
the people inside Kmart, there is a growing sense that we have
turned a corner-that we are finally and firmly on the road to
recovery. Our job now is to translate this enthusiasm into
tangible results. </p>
<p><font size="4"><b>A Strong Team</b></font> 
<p>There are a number of reasons to be optimistic about Kmart's future. For one, we have
assembled a strong group of senior executives with diverse
talents and backgrounds. Of the eight members of Kmart's
Executive Committee, five have joined the company within the last
18 months, including <b>Warren Flick</b>, president of U.S. Kmart
and chief architect of our merchandising strategy; <b>Ron Floto</b>,
president of our promising Super Kmart division; <b>Marv Rich</b>,
who is overseeing a major reengineering of our systems, work
processes and finances; <b>Warren Cooper</b>, who is heading up
our important human resources function; and myself. We are joined
by <b>Don Keeble</b>, head of our store operations; <b>Tom Watkins</b>
heading up our international retailing division; and <b>Tony
Palizzi</b>, our general counsel. </p>
<p>By tapping into the strong pool of talented managers already
in place at Kmart, our team has quickly begun to make a major impact
throughout the Company, creating a fundamental change in the way Kmart
does business. Our mission is to become the discount store of
choice for low and middle income families with children, and to
do so by satisfying their routine and seasonal shopping needs as well
as, or better than, our competitors. In the Executive Committee
report that follows this letter, you will learn more about the
specific merchandising, promotional and operational initiatives
we are implementing to fulfill this mission. We believe these
initiatives will result in improved merchandise assortments,
better in-stock positions, cleaner and more orderly stores, and
dramatic gains in customer service-all of which are intended to
translate into substantially improved financial results and enhanced
shareholder value. </p>
<p>The Board of Directors also has undergone a major reshaping. A
number of new members have joined the Board over the past year,
including <b>James B. Adamson</b>, <b>Stephen F. Bollenbach</b>, <b>Richard
G. Cline</b>, <b>Robert D. Kennedy</b>, <b>William P. Weber</b>,
and <b>James O. Welch, Jr.</b> These highly experienced and savvy
business leaders bring a wealth of experience and enthusiasm to
the task of overseeing Kmart's turn- around. They are worthy
successors to directors <b>David B. Harper</b>, <b>F. James MacDonald</b>, <b>Donald
S. Perkins</b>, <b>Lawence Perlman</b>, and <b>Gloria M. Shatto</b>,
who have retired after serving the company with grace and
distinction for many years. </p>
<p><font size="4"><b>Biting the Bullet</b></font> </p>
<p>Kmart's financial results for 1995 reflect the major financial
and strategic restructuring now underway at the Company. We &quot;bit
the bullet&quot; in 1995 and early 1996 in a number of ways: </p>
<ul>
    <li><p>We successfully concluded the disposition of many
        non-core assets. The Company has completed the sale of
        all of its investments in the Borders Group, OfficeMax,
        The Sports Authority, and Coles Myer. More recently, we
        also divested 860 automotive service centers in the U.S.
        to Penske Auto Center, Inc. and entered into a definitive agreement
        to sell our 13 eastern European stores to Tesco PLC. </p></li>
    <li><p>We closed 214 underperforming stores in the U.S.,
        eliminating those locations that were creating a
        significant cash drain on the Company. Some people have
        asked why we don't close another 500 stores; the answer
        is because we don't need to. With the exception of 30 to
        50 more stores that we plan to close this year, Kmart's
        stores are cash positive and located on strategically valuable
        real estate. </p></li>
    <li><p>We cleared out approximately $700 million in aged and
        discontinued inventory which was the major factor in our operational
        loss for the year. While the cost of removing this
        merchandise drove down our gross margins in 1995, the end
        result is that we have a better merchandise mix and more
        discipline throughout the buying process. </p></li>
    <li><p>And we undertook urgent financial action to address
        immediate problems. We eliminated the put provisions in agreements
        involving approximately $550 million of real estate
        related debt and restructured $2.7 billion in existing bank
        lines. These very difficult negotiations provide stability and
        near term confidence to the vendor community and prepare
        us for further restructuring in 1996. We also took a
        substantial non-cash writedown under FAS 121 for Builders
        Square and certain of Kmart's international operations.</p> </li>
</ul>
<p>All of these actions were painful, but they were essential to
reposition Kmart strategically and financially. As I write this letter,
we are focusing on continuing Kmart's sales momentum, further reducing expenses,
and improving margins as the first steps to restoring profits at
a reasonable level. </p>
<p>In 1995, comparable sales increased at a rate of 5.6% in our
U.S. Kmart stores and ended the year at $195 per square foot, the
highest level in several years. We intend to do even better in
1996 as we begin to roll out our new merchandising, marketing and
promotional strategies. </p>
<p>Given the current conditions in the retail industry, we cannot
rely only on sales gains to produce improved performance this year.
Accordingly, we are continuing our aggressive efforts to reduce selling, general
and administrative costs. Indeed, we intend to further reduce
SG&A costs by as much as $400 million this year. We also will
build more stability and flexibility into Kmart's balance sheet
by completing a restructuring of the Company's bank debt into a
multi-year revolving credit arrangement that better fits the
Company's seasonal needs. </p>
<p>From a cash flow perspective, we expect to see substantially
increased availability of cash from operating improvements, lower
dividend payments, conservative capital spending, and further dispositions
of non-core assets. We anticipate that our relationships with
suppliers will remain vigorous and healthy. </p>
<p>It may take time for all of these actions to find their way to
Kmart's bottom line. But one initiative that is already having a visible
impact on our performance is our renewed emphasis on store
cleanliness and customer service. For an experienced retailing
hand like me, there is nothing more important than whether or not
your stores sparkle and your sales associates are helpful. We
have made a lot of improvement in this area-and our customers are
beginning to take notice. </p>
<p>Although we are facing a difficult economic environment and
fierce competition, I am encouraged by Kmart's progress and excited
about the future. I genuinely believe that excellence-and
execution-will be the keys to Kmart's success. Excellence will
make Kmart the retailer of choice for our customers, the buyer of
choice for our suppliers, the employer of choice for our associates-and
the investment of choice for you, our shareholders. </p>
<p>I look forward to reporting to you on our progress as we
strive to reach this objective. 
</p>
<br>
</td>
</table>
